Probability distributions describe how the values of youtube dataset are distributed. Let’s understand all the probability distributions you should know as a Data Science professional:
 

 1. Uniform Distribution: In a uniform distribution, all outcomes are equally likely. It can be continuous or discrete.
 

 2. Normal (Gaussian) Distribution: The normal distribution, often called a "bell curve", is symmetrical. Most of the observations cluster around the central peak and probabilities for values further away from the mean taper off equally in both directions.
 

 3. Binomial Distribution: The binomial distribution represents the probability of having exactly k successes in n independent Bernoulli trials (yes/no outcome) with a constant probability of success p.
 

 4. Poisson Distribution: This distribution is a count distribution. It expresses the probability of a given number of events occurring in a fixed interval of time or space.
 

 5. Exponential Distribution: The exponential distribution describes the time between events in a process where events occur continuously and independently at a constant average rate.
 

 6. Log-Normal Distribution: A log-normal distribution is when the logarithm of the variable follows a normal distribution. It's skewed to the right, unlike the symmetric normal distribution.
 

 7. Chi-Squared Distribution: This distribution is the distribution of a sum of the squares of k independent standard normal random variables.
 

 8. t-Distribution: Similar to the normal distribution but with fatter tails, the t-distribution is used when the sample size is small and the population standard deviation is unknown.
 

 9. F-Distribution: An F-distribution arises from the ratio of two chi-squared distributions and is used in analysis of variance.

Hello Data Science freshers, here’s one advice for you all!
 

 If you are a fresher, always target Data Consulting companies for several obvious reasons that will become clear once you discover the reality.
 

 Data Consulting companies are the only companies where you will learn the actual use of data. You will be working with several problems and case studies in different projects.
 

 Targeting a product-based company as a fresher is not going to help you, as product-based companies outsource their most challenging data science projects to data consulting companies.
 

 Product-based companies mostly like to focus on their product, for which they hire domain experts. For example, a shoe company would prefer to offer more money to a supply chain analyst rather than a machine learning engineer.
 

 So, always target data consulting companies as a fresher to learn how to solve problems; otherwise, you will have experience in a product-based company but will always fear switching companies, as having more experience will make you go through tough interviews and hence is another reason for unemployment.
